WEBVTT

00:03.873 --> 00:05.048
Previously...

00:05.179 --> 00:06.765
You're not planning to eat
all of that, are you?

00:06.789 --> 00:07.833
No.

00:07.964 --> 00:09.226
I'm going to let it go moldy.

00:09.313 --> 00:10.619
I'm making penicillin,

00:10.749 --> 00:12.534
or at least I'm going to try to.

00:12.664 --> 00:14.504
The time has come
for you to fulfill your oath.

00:14.623 --> 00:16.364
Gather your men.

00:16.451 --> 00:17.471
I want Murtagh Fitzgibbons
and his insurgents

00:17.495 --> 00:18.627
brought to justice.

00:18.714 --> 00:20.759
Do not disappoint me, Colonel.

00:20.890 --> 00:21.934
Roger.

00:22.065 --> 00:23.197
If I call up a militia,

00:23.327 --> 00:24.391
he'll be expected to fight.

00:24.415 --> 00:25.938
He's not ready for that.

00:26.026 --> 00:29.072
- Captain Roger MacKenzie.
- Captain?

00:29.203 --> 00:31.118
Where is Murtagh Fitzgibbons?

00:31.205 --> 00:32.684
Ooh!

00:34.556 --> 00:36.993
You executed a man
without trial!

00:37.124 --> 00:38.429
Josiah, the hunter.

00:39.648 --> 00:40.866
Abscessed tonsils.

00:40.953 --> 00:42.390
I can remove them.

00:42.520 --> 00:43.715
If Claire does this for ye, lad,

00:43.739 --> 00:45.132
you'll settle at the Ridge?

00:45.262 --> 00:46.413
Do the hunting when I'm away?

00:46.437 --> 00:47.873
Thank ye.

01:00.712 --> 01:02.018
How d'ye ken what to look for?

01:05.413 --> 01:09.112
That is a very good question...

01:09.199 --> 01:11.767
just the sort of question
you should be asking.

01:13.029 --> 01:14.639
Well?

01:14.770 --> 01:17.164
Well, what sort
of teacher would I be

01:17.294 --> 01:19.296
if I simply gave you
all the answers?

01:20.341 --> 01:23.083
Now, how do you think
I know what to look for?

01:25.215 --> 01:26.215
From an experiment?

01:28.088 --> 01:29.915
From a book...

01:30.046 --> 01:32.962
in Boston, perhaps?

01:33.049 --> 01:37.184
They seem to have all sorts
of newfangled ideas
and things there.

01:38.750 --> 01:40.361
Yes, they do.

01:43.146 --> 01:44.365
So?

01:45.801 --> 01:50.414
So... the mold
is gray or white,

01:50.545 --> 01:52.460
ye said.

01:52.547 --> 01:53.896
Or...

01:54.026 --> 01:56.377
Light blue, sometimes green.

01:56.507 --> 01:59.554
Aye, and we're trying to avoid

01:59.641 --> 02:01.295
dark green and black.

02:01.425 --> 02:03.862
Those are the harmful molds.

02:03.993 --> 02:06.952
And the more food we have,
the more likely we are

02:07.083 --> 02:09.868
to find the kind of mold
that's useful as medicine.

02:09.999 --> 02:11.609
Very good.

02:11.696 --> 02:12.891
And soon we'll start
looking at it

02:12.915 --> 02:13.959
under a microscope.

02:16.571 --> 02:18.138
And what then?

02:18.225 --> 02:21.228
Well, then...
the real work begins.

02:24.231 --> 02:27.147
♪

02:35.372 --> 02:38.767
Jamie and I had tried
in the past and failed

02:38.854 --> 02:40.812
to stop history from happening.

02:40.943 --> 02:43.250
What I was doing now
was different.

02:43.380 --> 02:45.904
I was literally tempting fate,

02:46.035 --> 02:50.648
willing events to happen,
bringing the future forward.

02:50.779 --> 02:53.347
Penicillin was one
of those newfangled things

02:53.477 --> 02:56.393
I hoped would have a place
in the past,

02:56.524 --> 02:59.570
and I was daring history
to try and stop me.

02:59.744 --> 03:02.617
♪

03:16.587 --> 03:18.067
Damn.

03:18.676 --> 03:20.939
♪ Sing me a song ♪

03:21.113 --> 03:24.204
♪ Of a lass that is gone ♪

03:24.291 --> 03:26.336
♪ Say, could that lass ♪

03:26.510 --> 03:29.731
♪ Be I? ♪

03:29.905 --> 03:31.950
♪ Merry of soul ♪

03:32.037 --> 03:34.953
♪ She sailed on a day ♪

03:35.127 --> 03:36.868
♪ Over the sea ♪

03:37.042 --> 03:40.089
♪ To Skye ♪

03:40.263 --> 03:42.831
♪ Billow and breeze ♪

03:43.005 --> 03:45.312
♪ Islands and seas ♪

03:45.486 --> 03:48.271
♪ Mountains of rain and sun ♪

03:48.445 --> 03:50.752
♪ Mountains of rain
and sun ♪

03:50.926 --> 03:53.233
♪ All that was good ♪

03:53.407 --> 03:55.757
♪ All that was fair ♪

03:55.931 --> 03:57.933
♪ All that was me ♪

03:58.107 --> 04:00.805
♪ Is gone ♪

04:00.979 --> 04:03.199
♪ Sing me a song ♪

04:03.373 --> 04:06.158
♪ Of a lass that is gone ♪

04:06.246 --> 04:08.204
♪ Say, could that lass ♪

04:08.378 --> 04:11.425
♪ Be I? ♪

04:11.599 --> 04:13.557
♪ Merry of soul ♪

04:13.731 --> 04:16.691
♪ She sailed on a day ♪

04:16.865 --> 04:20.564
♪ Over the sea ♪

04:20.738 --> 04:26.701
♪ To Skye ♪

04:30.182 --> 04:32.533
♪

04:32.707 --> 04:36.754
♪ Sing me a song ♪

04:36.928 --> 04:39.061
♪ Of a lass ♪

04:39.148 --> 04:42.282
♪ That is gone ♪

04:42.456 --> 04:47.025
♪ Say, could that lass ♪

04:47.199 --> 04:51.203
♪ Be I? ♪♪♪

04:51.378 --> 04:53.205
♪

05:01.431 --> 05:04.347
♪

05:16.925 --> 05:19.884
♪

05:52.090 --> 05:53.309
Deo gratias.

05:53.483 --> 05:56.399
♪

06:05.234 --> 06:06.844
Jamie.

06:06.931 --> 06:09.891
♪

06:35.743 --> 06:38.136
What are you
thanking the Lord for?

06:38.310 --> 06:41.183
♪

06:45.622 --> 06:48.146
For the sight of you, Sassenach.

06:48.320 --> 06:51.236
♪

06:56.938 --> 06:58.548
- Oh.
- Hmm.

07:04.119 --> 07:05.599
You liked Lieutenant Knox.

07:09.385 --> 07:11.561
I did.

07:11.648 --> 07:14.172
Even though
Ethan provoked him, I...

07:14.303 --> 07:18.394
I didna think he'd act
so vengefully, so recklessly.

07:21.092 --> 07:23.747
You can't feel responsible
for the choices others make.

07:25.880 --> 07:29.013
You made yours
by freeing those men,

07:29.144 --> 07:30.885
and hopefully
it'll make a difference.

07:34.236 --> 07:36.281
That's what I fear.

07:36.412 --> 07:37.457
It willna.

07:39.197 --> 07:43.811
Those men told me
they have an army now.

07:43.941 --> 07:45.334
I saw it with my own eyes.

07:46.901 --> 07:49.251
They're not afraid
to face death.

07:51.427 --> 07:55.431
Right now... Murtagh's safe,

07:55.562 --> 07:57.172
and you're home.

07:59.435 --> 08:01.132
I've missed you.

08:04.745 --> 08:06.877
Everyone will be so happy
to have you back.

08:11.578 --> 08:14.494
I doubt our tenants
would share your sentiments,

08:14.624 --> 08:17.888
at least not those who swore an oath to me.

08:20.891 --> 08:22.414
I, uh...

08:29.247 --> 08:32.468
I must gather a militia,

08:32.555 --> 08:34.557
as many men as I can muster,

08:34.644 --> 08:37.212
return to Hillsborough
with all due speed.

08:41.303 --> 08:42.783
To fight?

08:47.614 --> 08:48.919
I hope not.

08:52.880 --> 08:56.448
Knox sent word,
asked Tryon for reinforcements.

08:58.146 --> 09:01.018
If I can gather enough men...

09:01.149 --> 09:03.238
A show of force to prevent war.

09:07.155 --> 09:09.723
Whatever happens
with the Regulators,

09:09.853 --> 09:13.465
there isn't anything written
about it, as far as I know.

09:13.553 --> 09:16.033
So it can't amount to much.

09:16.164 --> 09:18.775
Well, the man Knox killed might
disagree with the historians

09:18.906 --> 09:20.516
about what it amounts to.

09:24.476 --> 09:26.000
I'm coming with you.

09:28.785 --> 09:30.265
Uh...

09:30.395 --> 09:31.962
if there is a war
with the Regulators...

09:32.093 --> 09:34.225
Then you'll need a physician.

09:36.750 --> 09:38.969
You know, Murtagh, Knox, Tryon,

09:39.100 --> 09:40.580
they've all made their choices.

09:43.191 --> 09:44.888
And I've made mine.

09:47.499 --> 09:48.979
You need my help.

09:54.158 --> 09:55.682
I always have.

09:55.856 --> 09:58.728
♪

09:58.859 --> 10:00.512
And I always will.

10:00.687 --> 10:03.603
♪

10:10.000 --> 10:11.262
Grand-pére!

10:11.349 --> 10:12.481
Germain.

10:14.309 --> 10:16.006
Yer friend Thomas is here.

10:16.137 --> 10:17.377
Take this and share it wi' him.

10:17.486 --> 10:19.183
- Dinna tell yer ma.
- Oh.

10:26.408 --> 10:28.062
I saw Ronnie at the still.

10:28.192 --> 10:30.020
He said you were gathering
the militia.

10:30.151 --> 10:32.283
Aye.

10:32.414 --> 10:34.329
I'm glad ye're here.

10:34.459 --> 10:36.592
Perhaps ye could deliver
a advertisement

10:36.723 --> 10:38.855
to the printer
in Woolam's Creek.

10:38.986 --> 10:41.031
Let me fetch a pen
and some paper.

10:49.910 --> 10:52.739
♪

10:57.091 --> 10:58.483
Commencez.

10:58.614 --> 10:59.963
"Colonel James Fraser,

11:00.094 --> 11:02.313
"in command of a militia company

11:02.444 --> 11:05.099
"for Rowan County,

11:05.186 --> 11:07.928
"raised against the Regulators,

11:08.058 --> 11:10.539
"to all good and able men

11:10.670 --> 11:13.237
"between the age of 16 and 60.

11:13.368 --> 11:14.728
"I'll be passing through
the county

11:14.848 --> 11:17.154
"commencing on the 21st
of this month

11:17.285 --> 11:18.460
"to recruit men."

11:19.243 --> 11:21.637
- So soon?
- Aye.

11:21.768 --> 11:24.205
Have them print
a dozen broadsheets.

11:24.335 --> 11:26.729
We'll post them out
to the settlements hereabouts.

11:26.860 --> 11:28.620
I sent Roger Mac to tell
the men o' the Ridge

11:28.644 --> 11:30.646
we'll be leaving in a week.

11:30.777 --> 11:32.474
Ye'll be back
in time to join us.

11:32.604 --> 11:34.824
We'll be taking
yer whisky wi' us,

11:34.955 --> 11:36.957
share it wi' the men who enlist.

11:37.087 --> 11:40.134
It's the finest I've tasted
since leaving Scotland.

11:40.221 --> 11:42.005
I'm grateful, milord.

11:42.136 --> 11:44.660
As am I.
Go now.

11:44.834 --> 11:47.184
♪

11:47.271 --> 11:48.882
And hurry home.

11:48.969 --> 11:51.885
♪

12:46.504 --> 12:48.637
We'll gather more men
along the way,

12:48.768 --> 12:50.378
stop in Brownsville first.

12:50.508 --> 12:52.075
- Aye, Colonel.
- Aye, Colonel.

12:55.209 --> 12:57.211
♪

12:57.341 --> 13:00.170
I'm hoping ye willna
need use of it.

13:00.301 --> 13:01.301
Milord.

13:03.652 --> 13:05.785
A letter for you
has arrived from...

13:05.915 --> 13:09.484
Ah, I, uh...
I ken who sent it.

13:09.614 --> 13:10.790
Thank ye, lad.

13:13.096 --> 13:14.489
Thank you, Mistress Bug.

13:14.619 --> 13:15.620
And where's Mr. Trouble?

13:17.187 --> 13:18.627
You behave yourself
while we're away.

13:19.886 --> 13:21.365
Have a safe journey.

13:23.498 --> 13:25.108
Keep up your studies.

13:25.239 --> 13:26.999
You may have to sew up
a wound at some point.

13:27.110 --> 13:28.459
So keep practicing
your stitching.

13:28.590 --> 13:29.809
Mm-hmm.

13:31.158 --> 13:32.724
Remember?

13:32.812 --> 13:35.292
Pig flesh is a good substitute
for human tissue.

13:35.423 --> 13:36.816
Exactly.

13:36.946 --> 13:37.773
And I've left you some drawings

13:37.904 --> 13:39.470
of penicillium mold.

13:39.601 --> 13:41.516
So look in the microscope
like I showed you.

13:41.603 --> 13:44.214
- I will.
- Hmm.

13:44.345 --> 13:46.260
Bree, will you help Marsali
with her reading?

13:46.390 --> 13:47.435
Of course.

13:51.831 --> 13:53.789
I'm going to miss you.

13:55.573 --> 13:57.749
I'll write from Hillsborough

13:57.880 --> 14:00.361
if it looks like
we have to stay long.

14:00.491 --> 14:03.320
Bye, Mama.
Take care of yourself.

14:05.061 --> 14:07.194
Reminds me of the time I was

14:07.324 --> 14:09.444
saying good-bye to your father
on the station platform

14:09.500 --> 14:11.676
when I was going off to war.

14:11.807 --> 14:13.765
Mama, this is not
gonna be a war.

14:15.985 --> 14:17.204
I love you.

14:17.334 --> 14:18.509
I love you.

14:40.488 --> 14:43.447
I feel like Scarlett O'Hara,

14:43.578 --> 14:45.319
all the men leaving
the plantations.

14:52.369 --> 14:53.588
♪

14:53.718 --> 14:55.677
You should be honored.

14:56.460 --> 14:58.941
Jamie left you
in charge of the place.

14:59.072 --> 15:00.900
What does that even mean?

15:01.030 --> 15:04.164
Welcome to my world,
where no amount of studying

15:04.294 --> 15:06.514
can prepare you
for what's to come.

15:06.644 --> 15:09.386
Well, I guess that applies
to life in any time.

15:09.517 --> 15:11.171
Oh, there we are.

15:11.301 --> 15:13.521
There's that pioneering spirit
we're looking for.

15:13.695 --> 15:16.654
♪

15:31.452 --> 15:34.411
♪

16:03.397 --> 16:06.400
♪

16:06.530 --> 16:08.054
Push, lads! Push!

16:08.184 --> 16:10.317
One, two, three.

16:10.447 --> 16:12.145
Push!

16:12.275 --> 16:14.060
Well done, lads.

16:14.234 --> 16:17.106
♪

16:29.814 --> 16:32.382
Ronnie, take Evan and fetch
more wood for the fire.

16:32.513 --> 16:33.862
Looks to be a cold night.

16:33.993 --> 16:35.168
Aye, Colonel.

16:36.952 --> 16:41.000
There's, uh, something
I must tell you, Sassenach.

16:44.133 --> 16:47.006
♪

16:53.577 --> 16:57.494
I, uh... couldna tell ye
at the wedding.

16:58.669 --> 17:00.280
Then I left wi' Knox, and...

17:02.064 --> 17:03.152
I wanted to be certain.

17:03.239 --> 17:06.155
♪

17:08.114 --> 17:09.985
Stephen Bonnet is alive.

17:12.988 --> 17:15.947
♪

17:18.602 --> 17:21.083
But the explosion at the jail...

17:21.214 --> 17:23.520
Lord John told me that...

17:23.651 --> 17:25.348
Bonnet's body wasna found
among the rubble.

17:27.524 --> 17:28.644
He made further inquiries...

17:28.786 --> 17:31.920
♪

17:32.616 --> 17:35.880
Confirmed sightings of Bonnet
in Wilmington.

17:36.011 --> 17:37.360
He's smuggling again.

17:37.534 --> 17:40.624
♪

17:41.016 --> 17:42.800
Bree doesn't know, does she?

17:44.106 --> 17:45.455
No.

17:45.629 --> 17:48.676
♪

17:49.285 --> 17:51.157
Well, that's one small blessing.

17:53.115 --> 17:56.988
Aye, when I thought
Black Jack dead,

17:57.119 --> 17:58.686
it allowed me some peace.

18:00.644 --> 18:02.864
Peace from contemplating
revenge.

18:03.038 --> 18:06.259
♪

18:06.389 --> 18:09.218
Half o' me hopes never to see
that bastard Bonnet again.

18:09.392 --> 18:12.308
♪

18:15.790 --> 18:19.010
♪

18:19.141 --> 18:20.969
We'll not have time for drills.

18:21.056 --> 18:23.667
So we need to teach 'em
to fight like Highlanders:

18:23.798 --> 18:26.105
gather or scatter
on our command.

18:26.235 --> 18:27.235
Aye.

18:30.021 --> 18:32.198
All quiet out there, Colonel.

18:32.328 --> 18:34.330
Cold as charity, though.

18:34.417 --> 18:36.158
Mm.

18:36.289 --> 18:37.855
Fergus and Morton
are guarding the cart

18:37.942 --> 18:39.988
from bears and whatnot.

18:40.119 --> 18:43.774
Coldest damn spring
I can remember.

18:43.905 --> 18:45.254
I can barely feel my bollocks.

18:47.909 --> 18:49.709
Aye, I went for a pish,
but I couldna find it.

18:54.307 --> 18:56.004
Dinna put yer feet to the fire.

18:56.091 --> 18:57.460
Scorch the soles o' your boots
if ye're too close.

18:57.484 --> 18:59.138
See?

18:59.225 --> 19:01.025
Ah, it's better than setting
yer hair on fire.

19:01.052 --> 19:03.412
I dinna think my brother needs
to worry too much about that.

19:04.578 --> 19:05.883
Unlike Roger Mac, eh?

19:06.014 --> 19:08.321
He as furry as a bear.

19:08.408 --> 19:10.192
Aye, I'll go give
Fergus and Morton

19:10.323 --> 19:12.107
the fright of their lives.

19:14.457 --> 19:18.374
What say you, Mac Dubh, eh?
Heads or tails?

19:18.505 --> 19:20.507
Oh.
Ah, nae bother, lads.

19:20.637 --> 19:22.987
I'll sleep warm
no matter how I'm laid.

19:23.118 --> 19:25.207
Ooh!

19:25.294 --> 19:27.122
- Hmm?
- That's what you think.

19:31.909 --> 19:33.694
♪

19:35.870 --> 19:37.872
Stop! Thief!

19:37.959 --> 19:42.485
Stop! Thief!
Stop!

19:46.924 --> 19:47.924
- No!
- Come here.

19:47.969 --> 19:48.969
No!

19:49.100 --> 19:51.277
♪

19:51.407 --> 19:53.017
Caught him pilfering provisions.

19:53.148 --> 19:55.542
- Josiah?
- This is the hunter?

19:55.672 --> 19:57.326
What are you doing here?

19:57.413 --> 19:59.676
Fergus, can you get him
a blanket?

20:01.025 --> 20:04.115
Josiah... what's wrong?

20:04.203 --> 20:06.466
Wait.

20:06.596 --> 20:09.382
Didn't he have a scar
on his right hand?

20:11.035 --> 20:12.559
Yes, a thief's brand.

20:12.689 --> 20:13.951
He is that.

20:14.125 --> 20:16.258
♪

20:18.695 --> 20:21.611
♪

20:26.660 --> 20:28.139
Speak up, lad.

20:30.054 --> 20:32.927
That's Keziah... my brother.

20:33.014 --> 20:35.930
♪

20:44.243 --> 20:45.896
Look, lad,

20:45.983 --> 20:47.463
there's a bargain between us.

20:47.594 --> 20:49.857
Ye're my tenant.

20:49.944 --> 20:51.685
Ye have my protection.

20:51.815 --> 20:53.556
I have a right to the truth.

20:56.951 --> 20:59.475
Kezzie and I
are indentured to a man

20:59.606 --> 21:01.085
who lives not far from here.

21:02.391 --> 21:04.045
I ran away a year ago.

21:05.176 --> 21:07.440
Wi'out your brother?

21:07.570 --> 21:09.113
It isn't safe for him
in the woods with me.

21:09.137 --> 21:10.704
He can't hear nothing
coming up on him.

21:10.834 --> 21:12.074
I promised to come back for him

21:12.140 --> 21:13.750
when I had a situation
for myself,

21:13.881 --> 21:15.970
which I have now, thanks to you.

21:17.493 --> 21:19.843
So I went back for him
last night.

21:19.974 --> 21:22.890
We made camp in the woods,
and when I woke up...

21:23.847 --> 21:25.719
He has half starving
when I got him, sir.

21:25.849 --> 21:27.373
When he saw your provisions, I...

21:27.460 --> 21:28.939
Ye're welcome to the food, lad.

21:40.255 --> 21:41.952
Jo, more.

21:43.998 --> 21:45.956
He'd like some more.

21:47.436 --> 21:48.742
Of course.

21:59.056 --> 22:00.493
Has he always been deaf?

22:01.842 --> 22:04.148
Since we were five, Mistress.

22:04.279 --> 22:05.802
Our master boxed his ears.

22:08.892 --> 22:11.939
♪

22:12.069 --> 22:14.942
May I have a look?
Will you ask him?

22:15.072 --> 22:17.640
He can read your lips
when you talk, Mistress.

22:17.771 --> 22:20.948
And he knows words,
only he's shy about using 'em.

22:21.035 --> 22:22.645
♪

22:22.776 --> 22:26.083
May I have a look at your ears?

22:26.214 --> 22:27.868
Why isn't he wearing
any breeches?

22:27.998 --> 22:30.958
He took 'em off
in the barn where he slept.

22:31.088 --> 22:33.439
The barn cat
had her kittens on 'em.

22:33.526 --> 22:35.136
When I got him last night,

22:35.223 --> 22:37.268
he said he didn't want
to wake 'em.

22:37.443 --> 22:40.315
♪

22:51.805 --> 22:54.242
Ruptured eardrums.

22:54.373 --> 22:55.939
Surprised they haven't healed.

22:57.767 --> 22:59.552
Though I suspect
that wasn't the only time

22:59.682 --> 23:01.597
your master boxed your ears.

23:01.728 --> 23:02.511
Aye, Mistress.

23:02.685 --> 23:05.862
♪

23:06.167 --> 23:07.647
Have ye any other family, lad?

23:07.777 --> 23:09.997
No.

23:10.127 --> 23:14.828
We came across on a ship
with our parents
and our four sisters,

23:14.958 --> 23:16.830
but all of them perished
from illness at sea.

23:17.961 --> 23:19.572
So I'm told.

23:19.702 --> 23:22.052
We were but two.

23:22.183 --> 23:24.751
Mistress said we kent
only our Christian names.

23:24.838 --> 23:27.797
That was the first
Mistress Beardsley.

23:27.928 --> 23:29.514
Beardsley's the name
of the man who bought you.

23:29.538 --> 23:30.931
Aye.

23:31.061 --> 23:32.933
He's an Indian trader.

23:34.021 --> 23:36.589
Ship's captain sold us
for a term of 30 years.

23:38.068 --> 23:39.983
30 years?

23:40.114 --> 23:41.724
And that scar on your hand,

23:41.811 --> 23:43.354
that have anything to do
with your running away?

23:43.378 --> 23:46.555
I stole a cheese in town
and the dairymaid saw me.

23:46.686 --> 23:49.471
Sheriff branded me as a warning,

23:49.602 --> 23:51.647
but if Mr. Beardsley
found out...

23:53.606 --> 23:56.609
You won't send us back to him,
will you, Colonel Fraser?

23:57.610 --> 24:00.830
He beat us bad,
starved us, as ye can see.

24:02.919 --> 24:05.966
I willna send ye back.

24:06.096 --> 24:08.316
But I'll need to purchase
your indenture

24:08.447 --> 24:10.884
so he has no claim on ye.

24:11.014 --> 24:13.800
Is he home, d'ye ken,
or away trading?

24:13.887 --> 24:15.671
I canna say.

24:15.758 --> 24:18.935
But I saw his horse in the barn
when I got my brother.

24:19.066 --> 24:20.371
Be careful, sir.

24:20.546 --> 24:23.462
♪

24:26.508 --> 24:27.596
Captain.

24:27.770 --> 24:30.643
♪

24:34.603 --> 24:37.476
Take these lads
and the rest of the company

24:37.606 --> 24:39.565
and continue to Brownsville.

24:39.695 --> 24:42.916
Fill that muster book of yers
with as many men as ye can.

24:43.090 --> 24:45.179
♪

24:45.309 --> 24:47.268
Ye ken what's at stake here.

24:47.398 --> 24:49.488
I do.

24:49.618 --> 24:50.706
I won't let you down.

24:50.793 --> 24:53.927
♪

24:54.057 --> 24:57.800
Claire and I will go see
this Mr. Beardsley.

24:57.974 --> 25:00.890
♪

25:07.027 --> 25:09.333
I wonder how the dairymaid
could be certain it was Josiah

25:09.464 --> 25:11.292
who stole that cheese.

25:12.423 --> 25:14.904
You think it was Kezzie
but Josiah took the blame?

25:15.035 --> 25:16.950
And the punishment.
Aye, mebbe.

25:18.212 --> 25:19.605
He's a brave lad.

25:22.608 --> 25:26.220
Ye must cut that brand
off of him, Sassenach.

25:26.307 --> 25:28.135
There are thieftakers
in these parts.

25:29.832 --> 25:31.965
Will ye do it
like ye did for me?

25:32.052 --> 25:33.662
Of course.

25:33.793 --> 25:36.360
Ah, if we're to buy
his indenture,

25:36.491 --> 25:39.886
we must ensure
he's truly free of his past.

25:41.452 --> 25:43.367
Ah, we're here.

25:43.498 --> 25:45.892
Ho! The house!

25:47.241 --> 25:48.547
Whoa.

25:57.425 --> 25:59.514
You think they've gone
looking for the boy?

26:02.648 --> 26:04.345
Someone's home.

26:04.475 --> 26:05.651
I'll check the barn.

27:48.623 --> 27:51.582
♪

27:55.891 --> 27:56.891
Go away.

27:58.546 --> 28:00.330
Good morning to you, Mistress.

28:00.461 --> 28:02.289
I'm Colonel James Fraser
of Fraser's Ridge.

28:02.419 --> 28:04.552
I must speak with your husband.

28:04.683 --> 28:05.988
Husband's dead.

28:07.686 --> 28:09.035
I'm sorry to hear that.

28:09.165 --> 28:11.254
I must speak with ye, then.

28:11.385 --> 28:14.997
I've found myself in possession
of yer two bond servants,

28:15.128 --> 28:17.391
and I would like to purchase
their indentures.

28:17.521 --> 28:20.041
- I'm certain we can arrange...
- Keep 'em. I got no use for 'em

28:21.003 --> 28:23.876
♪

28:36.062 --> 28:37.541
Was that him?

28:39.630 --> 28:40.980
Beardsley's dead.

28:41.110 --> 28:42.721
I spoke with his wife.

28:42.851 --> 28:44.611
She told me to keep the lads,
free of charge.

28:44.679 --> 28:46.507
Well, that's good, isn't it?

28:48.030 --> 28:49.728
I need their papers.

28:49.815 --> 28:50.835
If we dinna have
their indentures,

28:50.859 --> 28:52.600
she could change her mind.

28:53.862 --> 28:57.692
Oh, there's something very
strange about this place, Jamie.

28:57.823 --> 28:59.389
We should go.

28:59.520 --> 29:00.869
I'll be quick.

29:15.928 --> 29:17.451
I need those papers.

29:20.976 --> 29:23.849
♪

29:51.224 --> 29:53.269
♪

29:55.750 --> 29:58.709
♪

30:05.673 --> 30:08.073
I don't know where
Mr. Beardsley would have
kept their papers.

30:12.985 --> 30:16.075
What about in that...
that desk there?

30:16.249 --> 30:19.078
♪

30:25.519 --> 30:26.999
Why do you keep
the goats indoors?

30:28.391 --> 30:30.393
It's too cold for 'em
in the barn.

30:31.525 --> 30:33.919
Too cold for the goats
but not for the bond servant?

30:35.050 --> 30:36.443
You want them papers or not?

30:37.531 --> 30:38.531
Ay.

30:39.750 --> 30:40.926
Aye, we do.

30:41.100 --> 30:44.277
♪

30:44.799 --> 30:45.844
Christ.

30:45.974 --> 30:47.193
What was that?

30:51.501 --> 30:52.720
Mrs. Beardsley.

30:55.723 --> 30:58.813
Shoo! Out! Come on, out.

30:58.944 --> 31:00.380
Tch. Shoo.

31:00.510 --> 31:01.685
Shoo, shoo.

31:06.342 --> 31:09.171
♪

31:14.350 --> 31:17.484
♪

31:17.614 --> 31:18.877
Stay away from there.

31:26.710 --> 31:29.931
That's just Billy.

31:30.018 --> 31:31.430
We keep him in there
so he doesn't rut

31:31.454 --> 31:33.500
with the others.

31:35.937 --> 31:37.504
Oh, God damn it.

31:37.634 --> 31:40.768
No, stay here.
Keep looking.

31:47.818 --> 31:50.038
Go! Tch! Tch!
Out! Out!

31:59.221 --> 32:00.875
Maybe he lost the papers.

32:03.225 --> 32:05.662
That smell...

32:07.186 --> 32:08.796
It isn't goat.

32:10.624 --> 32:12.843
I don't smell nothing.

32:13.018 --> 32:15.934
♪

32:22.288 --> 32:26.031
Your husband...
when did he die?

32:27.423 --> 32:29.077
A few months ago.

32:29.251 --> 32:32.167
♪

32:42.177 --> 32:44.136
What's upstairs?

32:44.266 --> 32:45.964
Don't go up there!

32:46.051 --> 32:48.967
♪

32:58.237 --> 33:01.109
♪

33:13.469 --> 33:16.385
♪

33:18.605 --> 33:21.564
♪

33:33.185 --> 33:34.882
Sassenach?

33:35.013 --> 33:36.405
Jamie!

33:36.579 --> 33:38.886
♪

33:41.758 --> 33:42.977
Sassenach!

33:48.461 --> 33:51.029
I think we found Mr. Beardsley.

33:52.682 --> 33:53.770
What's wrong with him?

33:53.857 --> 33:54.965
If I had to guess, I would say

33:54.989 --> 33:56.643
he suffered a stroke,

33:56.773 --> 33:58.601
an apoplexy, you'd call it.

33:59.907 --> 34:01.430
He's lying in his own filth.

34:01.561 --> 34:02.823
Aye.

34:02.953 --> 34:04.651
Here, hold this.

34:04.825 --> 34:07.741
♪

34:12.093 --> 34:14.748
Shh.
It's all right.

34:14.878 --> 34:17.446
Don't try to talk.

34:17.577 --> 34:19.187
We're here to help you.

34:22.451 --> 34:26.020
He's been lying here for weeks,
if not months.

34:26.107 --> 34:27.935
God's judgment, do ye think?

34:28.022 --> 34:30.981
♪

34:32.766 --> 34:35.551
Not entirely God's.
Look.

34:35.638 --> 34:39.164
She's been feeding him
just enough to keep him alive.

34:39.294 --> 34:41.253
In misery.

34:42.993 --> 34:44.343
Is there aught
ye can do for him?

34:44.517 --> 34:46.606
♪

34:46.736 --> 34:47.955
For the apoplexy, no.

34:48.042 --> 34:49.435
But to do a proper assessment,

34:49.565 --> 34:51.263
I need better light.

34:54.396 --> 34:56.529
♪

34:56.659 --> 34:58.618
You said he was dead.

34:58.748 --> 34:59.748
How did this happen?

34:59.836 --> 35:01.534
♪

35:01.664 --> 35:03.710
He chased me,

35:03.840 --> 35:05.886
struck me.

35:06.016 --> 35:07.801
He was in a rage as ever,
of course.

35:07.888 --> 35:11.109
- When?
- A month ago.

35:12.632 --> 35:13.952
Come up here
to get away from him.

35:14.024 --> 35:16.114
He followed me, and then he fell

35:16.201 --> 35:18.377
and lay writhing.

35:18.464 --> 35:20.030
I couldn't move him.

35:20.118 --> 35:22.468
Go prepare some hot water.

35:24.470 --> 35:25.949
We're bringing him down.

35:28.865 --> 35:32.042
♪

35:32.565 --> 35:34.480
Governor Tryon's orders:

35:34.610 --> 35:36.308
all able-bodied men
are asked to join

35:36.395 --> 35:38.048
His Excellency's militia.

35:38.136 --> 35:42.662
Poor men must bleed
for rich man's gold

35:42.792 --> 35:44.533
and always will, eh?

35:47.406 --> 35:51.061
Their father has gone to his
reward in heaven, or he'd join
ye.

35:52.889 --> 35:54.848
My condolences,
Mistress Findlay.

35:54.978 --> 35:57.329
Is there a reward for my sons?

35:57.459 --> 36:00.549
40 shillings each
from the governor's treasury

36:00.680 --> 36:03.378
and two shillings a day
for as long as they serve.

36:03.509 --> 36:05.206
And if they dinna
come out of it?

36:05.337 --> 36:07.339
I'll make sure they come home.

36:09.602 --> 36:11.212
Is that so?

36:14.041 --> 36:16.565
Well, then, Captain MacKenzie,

36:16.696 --> 36:20.352
I'll take yer word for it
that if I lend you my sons,

36:20.482 --> 36:22.528
ye'll send them home safe.

36:26.445 --> 36:28.447
So far as it lies in my power.

36:32.973 --> 36:34.888
Sign the book, lads.

36:34.975 --> 36:36.324
Yes, Ma.

36:37.804 --> 36:39.893
- Name?
- Hugh Findlay.

36:42.678 --> 36:44.550
Iain Og Findlay.

36:55.517 --> 36:58.128
He's covered in bedsores.

36:58.259 --> 37:00.479
His muscles have wasted away.

37:01.741 --> 37:03.699
At least the maggots
have kept his wounds clean.

37:05.179 --> 37:07.616
The man was trading goods.

37:08.878 --> 37:12.882
There are barrels of food
and bundles of furs out there.

37:14.797 --> 37:17.060
Yet he lay where he fell,

37:17.147 --> 37:18.801
cold, starving.

37:21.978 --> 37:23.937
Why'd she no' simply
let him die?

37:29.725 --> 37:31.640
So she could do this.

37:34.687 --> 37:36.123
♪

37:36.254 --> 37:37.777
Can he be healed?

37:40.780 --> 37:42.671
Should ye not be looking
for the indenture papers?

37:42.695 --> 37:45.567
♪

37:50.442 --> 37:52.835
She tried to bleed him
to heal him?

37:52.966 --> 37:55.142
No. Look at his feet.

37:56.970 --> 37:59.494
She burns them over and over,

37:59.625 --> 38:01.279
lets them heal,
and then does it again.

38:01.366 --> 38:03.324
♪

38:03.455 --> 38:04.717
She was torturing him.

38:09.243 --> 38:11.593
♪

38:11.724 --> 38:13.595
I think he understands you,
Sassenach.

38:13.769 --> 38:16.685
♪

38:16.772 --> 38:18.252
Can ye, man?

38:19.688 --> 38:21.908
Did yer wife do this to ye?

38:27.087 --> 38:29.219
Blink once for yes.

38:29.394 --> 38:32.266
♪

38:37.750 --> 38:40.840
What you must have done
to deserve this.

38:43.886 --> 38:46.802
♪

39:01.817 --> 39:04.516
His right foot's gangrenous.

39:04.646 --> 39:08.171
I'll have to amputate soon,
or it'll spread and he'll die.

39:08.302 --> 39:11.261
I need a saw and something
to sterilize it with.

39:11.392 --> 39:12.915
I can cauterize the wound
and then...

39:13.046 --> 39:15.265
We dinna have time, Claire,
to do the surgery

39:15.396 --> 39:18.399
and give him time to heal.

39:18.530 --> 39:22.142
I must rejoin the company
and go on to Hillsborough.

39:22.272 --> 39:25.972
I know, but I can't
leave him like this.

39:26.059 --> 39:28.975
If I can find a way
to make him comfortable enough,

39:29.105 --> 39:30.735
then we can bring him with us
to Brownsville

39:30.759 --> 39:32.359
and find someone there
to look after him.

39:32.457 --> 39:33.980
Then perhaps...

39:34.110 --> 39:35.547
No!

39:35.677 --> 39:36.983
No. Fanny.

39:42.728 --> 39:45.383
No.

39:45.470 --> 39:48.037
She would have saved him.
He should die!
I want him to die!

39:48.168 --> 39:49.667
Ye could ha' killed him
at yer leisure!

39:49.691 --> 39:51.214
Why in God's name would ye wait

39:51.345 --> 39:52.888
- until ye had witnesses?
- I didn't want him dead.

39:52.912 --> 39:55.175
I wanted him to die slowly!

39:55.305 --> 39:56.742
You filthy beast!

39:56.872 --> 39:58.961
You dirty, wicked...

39:59.092 --> 40:01.181
I'm his wife.
Let him rot!

40:12.540 --> 40:13.759
The babe.

40:15.543 --> 40:17.153
Ugh.

40:21.288 --> 40:23.203
Big push, come on.

40:23.333 --> 40:26.249
That's it.

40:28.121 --> 40:29.905
Here.
Okay, one more.

40:30.036 --> 40:31.298
Come on.

40:35.868 --> 40:36.912
Oh!

40:41.526 --> 40:43.615
There we go, little girl.

40:43.745 --> 40:45.094
Here.

40:47.140 --> 40:48.924
Well done.

40:49.011 --> 40:51.840
Jamie.

40:51.971 --> 40:54.234
Ah.

40:54.364 --> 40:56.628
All right.

40:56.758 --> 40:59.195
Now, the afterbirth.

40:59.282 --> 41:02.285
Small push more, all right?

41:03.896 --> 41:05.419
Come on!

41:05.550 --> 41:06.812
That's it.

41:10.729 --> 41:12.252
Well done.

41:13.906 --> 41:15.473
Claire.

41:18.606 --> 41:21.479
♪

41:25.395 --> 41:27.441
Heh.

41:27.572 --> 41:29.965
The baby's skin.

41:30.096 --> 41:31.227
Huh.

41:33.099 --> 41:35.318
It would appear

41:35.449 --> 41:38.496
the baby father's is black.

41:38.626 --> 41:40.062
Let me see her.

41:40.236 --> 41:42.891
♪

41:47.853 --> 41:49.855
You have a beautiful baby girl.

41:53.685 --> 41:56.514
She isn't his.

41:59.081 --> 42:02.563
You hear that, you old bastard?

42:02.650 --> 42:04.130
She isn't yours.

42:06.262 --> 42:08.134
She isn't yours!

42:16.446 --> 42:18.144
Oh, she isn't his.

42:18.318 --> 42:21.190
♪

42:35.161 --> 42:37.598
Do you have any family nearby?

42:37.729 --> 42:41.341
He took me from my fathers
house in Baltimoe

42:41.471 --> 42:42.734
to this place.

42:46.476 --> 42:48.087
I miss Baltimore.

42:51.090 --> 42:52.570
How long ago was that?

42:54.136 --> 42:57.531
Two years... three months,
and five days.

43:01.709 --> 43:03.493
Those are your markings
on the door.

43:04.973 --> 43:07.062
No.

43:07.193 --> 43:09.804
That was Mary Ann, I believe.

43:11.763 --> 43:14.156
That was his first wife?

43:14.287 --> 43:15.767
No.

43:17.246 --> 43:18.552
Mary Ann was his fourth.

43:18.726 --> 43:21.555
♪

43:21.686 --> 43:23.513
You're his fifth?

43:23.688 --> 43:26.995
♪

43:28.301 --> 43:30.564
The others are buried in the
woods under the rowan tree.

43:30.738 --> 43:33.175
♪

43:33.306 --> 43:36.875
I see their ghosts sometimes,

43:37.005 --> 43:39.138
especially Mary Ann.

43:39.268 --> 43:40.879
She tells me things.

43:41.053 --> 43:43.446
♪

43:45.318 --> 43:46.798
He killed them all, you know.

43:48.843 --> 43:50.802
He would have killed me too.

43:50.889 --> 43:52.760
None of us could give him
a baby.

43:52.934 --> 43:55.850
♪

44:01.247 --> 44:03.728
Who is the father,
if you don't mind me asking?

44:03.902 --> 44:06.121
♪

44:06.252 --> 44:07.383
A good man.

44:07.557 --> 44:09.821
♪

44:09.951 --> 44:11.649
Does he live nearby?

44:11.736 --> 44:14.652
♪

44:18.307 --> 44:20.440
He beat us terrible,

44:20.570 --> 44:22.877
me and those boys,
all three of us.

44:24.662 --> 44:27.273
If I c-if I could find
their papers,

44:27.403 --> 44:28.666
I'd give 'em to you.

44:30.624 --> 44:33.496
They deserve some happiness,
I suppose.

44:33.583 --> 44:36.543
So should you

44:36.674 --> 44:37.936
and your baby.

44:38.110 --> 44:41.069
♪

44:44.638 --> 44:46.509
Even though she's born
of her mother's sin?

44:46.640 --> 44:48.468
Yes.

44:48.642 --> 44:50.949
♪

44:51.079 --> 44:52.777
Hopefully she was born
out of love.

44:52.951 --> 44:55.518
♪

44:55.649 --> 44:57.956
She'll need more than love
to get by in this world.

44:58.130 --> 44:59.914
♪

45:00.045 --> 45:02.787
You have the property...

45:02.917 --> 45:04.440
this home.

45:04.527 --> 45:08.401
This place
is her birthright, but...

45:08.488 --> 45:11.491
but to me, it's naught
but ugliness and evil.

45:11.578 --> 45:15.103
We will take your husband with us to town.

45:15.234 --> 45:17.323
He can't harm you anymore.

45:17.497 --> 45:19.847
♪

45:19.978 --> 45:21.501
You're a mother now.

45:21.675 --> 45:24.809
♪

45:25.723 --> 45:30.510
Having a baby...
doesn't make me a mother

45:30.597 --> 45:34.122
any more than sleeping in a
stable makes someone a horse.

45:37.212 --> 45:40.128
♪

45:47.222 --> 45:49.181
Maybe when you name her...

45:49.355 --> 45:51.879
♪

45:52.010 --> 45:53.272
I'm so sorry.

45:54.795 --> 45:56.797
I forgot to ask you your name.

45:58.190 --> 45:59.321
It's Frances.

45:59.495 --> 46:01.759
♪

46:01.889 --> 46:04.936
My mother used to call me Fanny.

46:06.938 --> 46:08.330
It's supposed to mean "free."

46:08.504 --> 46:10.376
♪

46:10.506 --> 46:13.422
And your name is...
Sassenach.

46:14.902 --> 46:17.383
♪

46:17.513 --> 46:19.167
Only to my husband.

46:19.341 --> 46:22.214
♪

46:23.215 --> 46:25.086
You can call me Claire.

46:25.260 --> 46:28.176
♪

46:32.267 --> 46:35.140
♪

46:42.930 --> 46:45.803
♪

46:52.331 --> 46:55.247
Shh.

47:03.342 --> 47:05.126
How long
will ye have to stay here?

47:07.172 --> 47:08.651
A day or two at the least.

47:10.262 --> 47:12.220
We'll need to find someone
to look in on them.

47:14.092 --> 47:15.658
I know you're anxious
to get going.

47:23.144 --> 47:24.929
What will we do about him?

47:26.452 --> 47:27.932
Oh, I don't know.

47:30.543 --> 47:32.850
As a doctor, I can't
walk away, but...

47:34.721 --> 47:36.418
I'm not sure
you owe him anything.

47:40.770 --> 47:42.598
Well, they are our neighbors.

47:46.341 --> 47:48.909
What kind of world is this
to bring a baby into?

47:52.130 --> 47:53.653
The only world.

47:56.786 --> 47:58.745
No, it isn't.

48:01.835 --> 48:03.619
♪

48:03.750 --> 48:07.406
Jamie...
I want Brianna and Roger

48:07.536 --> 48:09.190
to go back to their own time

48:09.277 --> 48:11.932
as soon as they know
if Jemmy can travel.

48:12.063 --> 48:15.066
It's safer for them there,

48:15.196 --> 48:16.676
for Jemmy especially.

48:16.850 --> 48:19.809
♪

48:21.681 --> 48:23.944
Roger feels the same way.

48:24.031 --> 48:25.250
He wants to take them home.

48:25.337 --> 48:26.773
Of course he does.

48:28.079 --> 48:31.082
Your penicillin will make it
safer for them here,
will it not?

48:31.212 --> 48:32.953
Only from infection.

48:34.607 --> 48:38.045
Well, perhaps it would be
safer in your time.

48:39.655 --> 48:42.920
But they would be
without their family,

48:43.050 --> 48:44.399
without their blood.

48:44.486 --> 48:47.881
♪

48:48.012 --> 48:50.884
Come...

48:50.971 --> 48:54.105
♪

48:54.583 --> 48:55.889
Put these thoughts away.

48:56.063 --> 48:58.544
♪

48:58.674 --> 49:00.546
Sleep.

49:00.720 --> 49:03.636
♪

49:18.912 --> 49:21.828
♪

49:57.995 --> 50:00.127
What is it?

50:00.214 --> 50:01.520
Fanny?

50:03.348 --> 50:06.003
- The baby?
- Still here.

50:07.743 --> 50:09.049
Where could she have gone?

50:09.136 --> 50:10.311
I'll look outside.

50:30.940 --> 50:33.117
Oh, shh.

50:46.608 --> 50:49.133
♪

50:51.483 --> 50:53.354
Her horse is gone.

50:53.485 --> 50:54.877
Mebbe she's gone to find help.

50:56.401 --> 50:57.489
She's not coming back.

50:57.663 --> 50:59.882
♪

51:00.013 --> 51:02.059
She left these with the baby.

51:02.972 --> 51:04.452
The deed.

51:04.626 --> 51:07.542
♪

51:16.725 --> 51:17.987
And indenture papers.

51:18.162 --> 51:21.382
♪

51:22.122 --> 51:24.211
She means for us to keep her.

51:24.385 --> 51:27.301
♪

51:32.785 --> 51:35.701
♪

51:54.676 --> 51:57.592
We'll have goat's milk
for the journey.

51:57.723 --> 51:59.048
Hopefully there'll be
a nursing mother

51:59.072 --> 52:00.552
in Brownsville.

52:00.682 --> 52:03.337
And we'll seek Mrs. Beardsley
as we travel.

52:03.468 --> 52:04.817
We won't find her.

52:08.255 --> 52:09.735
What do we do about him?

52:13.260 --> 52:15.088
Take the bairn outside.

52:15.175 --> 52:16.611
Dinna come back
until I call for ye.

52:18.831 --> 52:21.529
- Jamie...
- I would do it for a dog,
Claire.

52:21.660 --> 52:23.052
Could I do less for him?

52:23.227 --> 52:25.533
♪

52:25.664 --> 52:27.709
Go.

52:27.840 --> 52:30.886
Let it be his choice, his will.

52:32.540 --> 52:35.761
If or if not,
I will call for ye.

52:35.935 --> 52:38.894
♪

53:18.543 --> 53:21.807
Blink once for yes,
twice for no.

53:23.809 --> 53:24.897
Do ye understand?

53:27.160 --> 53:30.076
♪

53:34.298 --> 53:35.647
Yer wife is gone.

53:37.518 --> 53:39.607
Ye ken the child isna yers.

53:39.781 --> 53:42.654
♪

53:49.704 --> 53:52.577
♪

53:58.844 --> 54:01.847
My wife is a healer,

54:01.977 --> 54:05.329
says you suffered an apoplexy,

54:05.416 --> 54:07.156
canna be cured of it.

54:08.854 --> 54:10.508
Your foot is putrid.

54:12.161 --> 54:14.729
If it's not taken off,
ye'll rot and die.

54:16.862 --> 54:18.298
D'ye understand?

54:21.388 --> 54:24.304
♪

54:27.394 --> 54:30.702
Would ye have her take your foot
and tend to your wounds?

54:30.876 --> 54:33.792
♪

54:43.497 --> 54:45.847
Do you ask me to take yer life?

54:46.021 --> 54:48.894
♪

55:01.341 --> 55:03.169
By all accounts,
you are a wicked man.

55:04.823 --> 55:07.739
I have no wish to send a soul to hell.

55:07.826 --> 55:09.741
Will ye pray for forgiveness?

55:09.915 --> 55:12.874
♪

55:21.361 --> 55:24.321
♪

55:26.497 --> 55:28.281
Then may God forgive us both.

55:28.455 --> 55:31.328
♪

55:40.902 --> 55:44.036
♪

56:11.846 --> 56:14.719
♪

56:21.029 --> 56:22.988
I thought apoplexy
killed a man outright.

56:23.162 --> 56:26.339
♪

56:26.470 --> 56:30.125
Never thought to ask Jenny
if my father suffered.

56:30.299 --> 56:33.215
♪

56:34.260 --> 56:35.783
She would have told you.

56:35.957 --> 56:38.351
♪

56:38.482 --> 56:39.787
Perhaps.

56:39.961 --> 56:42.877
♪

56:48.317 --> 56:50.276
She would have.

56:50.407 --> 56:53.714
Swear to me, Claire...

56:53.845 --> 56:55.205
if it should one day
fall to my lot

56:55.281 --> 56:58.415
as it did to my father...

56:58.545 --> 57:03.028
swear to me that ye will
give me the same mercy
that I gave that wretch.

57:03.202 --> 57:06.118
♪

57:10.252 --> 57:11.863
I'll do what must be done.

57:12.037 --> 57:15.170
♪

57:18.565 --> 57:21.481
♪
